07491nam a22009495i 9780271094168DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710941687 a10.1515/97802710941682doi  a(DE-B1597)626193  a(OCoLC)1303084968  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBX7990.H6bH57 2022 7aREL1080202bisacsh04a280/.4223/eng/2021101400aHoliness and Pentecostal Movements :bIntertwined Pasts, Presents, and Futures /ced. by Geordan Hammond, David Bundy, David Sang-Ehil Han. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (282 p.) :b15 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in the Holiness and Pentecostal Movements ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction: Intertwined History, Theology, and Scholarship -- tAt the Beginning -- t1. The Preachers and Their Students: God’s Bible School as a Seedbed of Radical Holiness and Pentecostal Leaders, 1892–1910 -- t2. Pandita Ramabai, the Holiness Movement, and the Mukti Revival of 1905 -- t3. Alexander A. Boddy, the Pentecostal League of Prayer, and the Wesleyan Roots of British Pentecostalism -- t4. A World Tour of Evangelism: Henry Clay Morrison’s Radical Holiness Meets “Global Holiness,” 1909–10 -- tUnity and Diversity -- t5. “Spiritual Railroading”: Trains as Metaphor and Reality in the Holiness and Pentecostal Movements, ca. 1880–ca. 1920 -- t6. Black Radical Holy Women at the Intersection of Christian Unity and Social Justice -- t7. Pneumatology as a Basis for Ecumenical Dialogue Between the Korean Methodist, Holiness, and Pentecostal Traditions -- tTheological Engagement -- t8. Baptized in the Spirit and Fire: The Relevance of Spirit Baptism for a Holiness and Pentecostal View of the Atonement -- t9. The Presence of the Kingdom: Optimism of Grace in the Holiness and Pentecostal Movements -- t10. Fulfilling the Full Gospel: The Promise of the Theology of the Cleveland School -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the 1830s, Holiness and Pentecostal movements have had a significant influence on many Christian churches, and they have been a central force in producing what is known today as World Christianity. This book demonstrates the advantages of analyzing them in relation to one another.The Salvation Army, the Church of the Nazarene, the Wesleyan Church, and the Free Methodist Church identify strongly with the Holiness Movement. The Assemblies of God and the Pentecostal Assemblies of the World identify just as strongly with the Pentecostal Movement. Complicating matters, denominations such as the Church of God (Cleveland), the International Holiness Pentecostal Church, and the Church of God in Christ have harmonized Holiness and Pentecostalism. This book, the first in the new series Studies in the Holiness and Pentecostal Movements, examines these complex relationships in a multidisciplinary fashion. Building on previous scholarship, the contributors provide new ways of understanding the relationships, influences, and circulation of ideas among these movements in the United States, the United Kingdom, India, and Southeast and East Asia.In addition to the editors, the contributors are Kimberly Ervin Alexander, Insik Choi, Robert A. Danielson, Chris E. W. Green, Henry H. Knight III, Frank D. Macchia, Luther Oconer, Cheryl J. Sanders, and Daniel Woods.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHoliness movementxHistory. 0aHoliness movement. 0aPentecostalismxHistory. 0aPentecostalism. 7aRELIGION / Christian Church / History.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Kimberly Ervin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca